Teheran deports Al-Qaeda suspects
TEHERAN - Iran has extradited suspected members of the Al-Qaeda terror organisation who were recently identified while in custody, a government spokesman said.
Mr Abdollah Ramazanzadeh, Iran's government spokesman, told the Financial Times that those suspects who had been identified and were from countries with 'friendly relations' with Iran had been extradited.
He declined to give details.
He also told a news conference on Monday that detainees who had committed crimes in Iran, or were from countries without good relations with the Islamic republic, would be prose- cuted by Iranian courts.
The United States, which broke ties with Teheran after the 1979 Islamic Revolution, accuses Iran of seeking nuclear weapons and med- dling in post-war Iraq.
Washington also says senior figures of the terror group are operating in Iran near the border with Afghanistan.
Shi'ite Muslim Iran rejects all the charges and says it was always ideologically opposed to the Sunni Al-Qaeda network which Washington accuses of masterminding the Sept 11, 2001 attacks on US cities.
US officials alleged that Al-Qaeda operatives in Iran had planned the May 12 suicide bombing attacks in Riyadh, Saudi Arabia, that killed 34 people, including eight Americans.
The US cancelled a planned meeting with Iranian officials on the subject of Iraq in protest against the suspected involvement.
Recent visits to Teheran by Prince Saud, Foreign Minister of Saudi Arabia, and Sheikh Muhammad Khalid al-Ahmad al-Sabah, Kuwait's Interior Minister, suggest to diplomats that some of the suspects detained in Iran may be from the two Gulf Arab states.
Last year, Teheran deported several hundred members of Al-Qaeda and their relatives who had fled to Iran after the US-led campaign in Afghanistan.
US newspapers reported last month that Al-Qaeda suspects possibly in detention in Iran included Suleiman Abu Ghaith, a Kuwaiti who acted as the organisation's spokesman, and Saif al-Adel, an Egyptian believed to be its security chief.
Separately, Iran is asking France to extradite members of the People's Mujahideen Organisation (MKO).
The MKO is an opposition group that has carried out armed attacks inside Iran.
Security forces raided MKO-affiliated offices near Paris last week and 17 suspects remain in detention.
A French official said there would be no extradition to Iran. -- Financial Times,Reuters Subscribe to The Straits Times print edition today.
